b"I don't like the idea of a principal spanking a student, but I don't have as much an issue with students getting in trouble for walk outs as many do.

Protest is not a part of the curriculum.

I'm not a parent, but if I were, I'd hope my child would take an informed stand yay or nay and do what he deems right and be willing to take the consequences for it.

I think it'd be a source of pride to know I didn't raise a lemming, even if I'm frustrated by the position.

The Civil Rights Movement was largely a protest of children who disobeyed all and many paid for it for their entire lives--lost educational or job opportunities, estrangement from parents who lost their entire livelihood due to their participation, having to move up North for safety. . . 

Those children were threatened by their families, school, and society not to take part, yet there are reports that teachers would have their backs to the class to jot something on the board only to turn around and find the classroom was empty because all the children went to go march with King, Jr.

That's what made their choices powerful.

The traditional school walkout is kind of a form of petty civil disobedience. It's not something you get consent for, so it's something one ought to expect consequences for taking part in.

b'Is a person who is intersex a hermaphrodite?

No. The mythological term "hermaphrodite" implies that a person is both fully male and fully female. This is a physiologic impossibility.

The words "hermaphrodite" and "pseudo-hermaphrodite" are stigmatizing and misleading words. Unfortunately, some medical personnel still use them to refer to people with certain intersex conditions, because they still subscribe to an outdated nomenclature that uses gonadal anatomy as the basis of sex classification. In a paper titled Changing the Nomenclature/Taxonomy for Intersex: A Scientific and Clinical Rationale, five ISNA-associated experts recommend that all terms based on the root "hermaphrodite" be abandoned because they are scientifically specious and clinically problematic. The terms fail to reflect modern scientific understandings of intersex conditions, confuse clinicians, harm patients, and panic parents. We think it is much better for everyone involved when specific condition names are used in medical research and practice.'

Section 2. Representatives shall be apportioned among the several States according to their respective numbers, counting the whole number of persons in each State, excluding Indians not taxed. Section 3. No person shall be a Senator or Representative in Congress, or elector of President and Vice President, or hold any office, civil or military, under the United States, or under any State, who, having previously taken an oath, as a member of Congress, or as an officer of the United States, or as a member of any State legislature, or as an executive or judicial officer of any State, to support the Constitution of the United States, shall have engaged in insurrection or rebellion against the same, or given aid or comfort to the enemies thereof. But Congress may, by a vote of two-thirds of each House, remove such disability.

Section 4. The validity of the public debt of the United States, authorized by law, including debts incurred for payment of pensions and bounties for services in suppressing insurrection or rebellion, shall not be questioned. But neither the United States nor any State shall assume or pay any debt or obligation incurred in aid of insurrection or rebellion against the United States, or any claim for the loss or emancipation of any slave; but all such debts, obligations and claims shall be held illegal and void.

b'Ok, I admit that I'm being intentionally incendiary with the last bit but the point is still valid. There is a worrying and rising trend of victim mentalities and persecution culture happening within society and it's driven by this notion that people suddenly have some kind of legal power just because they don't agree with something. People are suing, and winning, compensation because of "hurt feelings" which is absolutely insane. It's a worrying precedent when left leaning people (particularly in universities) look at speakers like Ben Shapiro, Jordan Peterson, Sam Harris etc and decide it's ok to say they should be fired/sued/arrested/silenced (take your pick) just for holding a viewpoint. I don't agree with a lot of what those speakers say but I don't see how it's legitimate to bring legal action just because I feel like I've somehow been emotionally displeased by their actions/words. TYT are directly responsible for promoting this crazy militant left viewpoint of "I disagree therefore I can do whatever I want" that is becoming just as toxic, divisive and damaging as those on the right. 

The same logic applies here. I find it pretty insane that an individual feels like they can sue a President for blocking them on Twitter. It screams of leftist "I am a victim because I don't like you" hyper-sensitivity that is creeping into society. 

But I'm happy to discuss it on the constitutional point you've raised because I think there may be some grounds of debate there. 

Pt1 - I see the basis of your point but I disagree that it denies the right to dissent. Twitter is just one of many avenues for statements and rebuttals. Denying the right to dissent makes it sound like this person is being locked up as a political prisoner when it's a million miles away. On top of that, where do you draw the line? If someone is banned from a rally, is that the same thing? If someone like Shapiro is banned from a university, are you applying the same laws of free speech etc to that situation?

Pt2 - Again, I see your point but my answer is the same. Twitter is not an official platform for policy. Also, I do think that, as it's his personal account and not POTUS, the allegation is on more questionable foundation than if it was POTUS account. On the point in the video about communication with the Govt, does the plaintiff really think Trump is the entire Government? They're acting as if The President is really going to change Govt policy just because someone on Twitter responded to him and now the country is like 1984 just because of this. 

Pt3 - I've covered above

Pt4 - I don't think the individual is being censored in the slightest. Trump hasn't called for the person to be removed from Twitter or anything like that so I find it hard to argue that the person's right to free speech is in any way inhibited. Like I said above, if it's about policy, they can go to POTUS account, the Govt website, the news, pretty much anywhere else. 

On the whole, whilst I see what they're trying to argue legally, I really don't think this person is suing because they really miss reading updates on policy decisions. It smacks plainly of a highly strung, overly-entitled and overly emotional person that is suing just because they hate Trump and they've been told by people like TYT that they have an opinion that everyone else should listen to just because they feel a bit upset.'

b'The cases turned up during a 2006 ICE inquiry, called Project Flicker, which targeted overseas processing of child-porn payments. As part of the probe, ICE investigators gained access to the names and credit card information of more than 5,000 Americans who had subscribed to websites offering images of child pornography. Many of those individuals provided military email addresses or physical addresses with Army or fleet ZIP codes when they purchased the subscriptions.

In a related inquiry, the Pentagon's Defense Criminal Investigative Service (DCIS) cross-checked the ICE list against military databases to come up with a list of Defense employees and contractors who appeared to be guilty of purchasing child  pornography. The names included staffers for the secretary of defense, contractors for the ultra-secretive National Security Agency, and a program manager at the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency. But the DCIS opened investigations into only 20 percent of the individuals identified, and succeeded in prosecuting just a handful.

The Boston Globe first reported the Pentagon's role in Project Flicker in July, citing DCIS investigative reports (PDF) showing that at least 30 Defense Department employees were investigated.

But new Project Flicker investigative reports obtained by The Upshot through the Freedom of Information Act, which you can read here, show that DCIS investigators identified 264 Defense employees or contractors who had purchased child pornography online. Astonishingly, nine of those had "Top Secret Sensitive Compartmentalized Information" security clearances, meaning they had access to the nation's most sensitive secrets. All told, 76 of the individuals had Secret or higher clearances. But DCIS investigated only 52 of the suspects, and just 10 were ever charged with viewing or purchasing child pornography. Without greater public disclosure of how these cases wound down, it's impossible to know how or whether any of the names listed in the Project Flicker papers came in for additional scrutiny. It's conceivable that some of them were picked up by local law enforcement, but it seems likely that most of the people flagged by the investigation did not have their military careers disrupted in the context of the DCIS inquiry.'
